  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The same rules apply to the peace-offerings of sheep and goats, except that, in addition to the fat portions, which were to be burned upon the altar in the case of the oxen (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and goats (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the fat tail of the sheep was to be consumed as well. תמימה האליה: \"the fat tail whole\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), cauda ovilla vel arietina eaque crassa et adiposa; the same in Arabic (Ges. thes. p. 102). The fat tails which the sheep have in Northern Africa and Egypt, also in Arabia, especially Southern Arabia, and Syria, often weigh 15 lbs. or more, and small carriages on wheels are sometimes placed under them to bear their weight (Sonnini, R. ii. p. 358; Bochart, Hieroz. i. pp. 556ff.). It consists of something between marrow and fat. Ordinary sheep are also found in Arabia and Syria; but in modern Palestine all the sheep are \"of the broad-tailed species.\" The broad part of the tail is an excresence of fat, from which the true tail hangs down (Robinson, Pal. ii. 166). \"Near the rump-bone shall he (the offerer) take it (the fat tail) away,\" i.e., separate it from the body. עצם, ἁπ. λεγ., is, according to Saad., os caudae s. coccygis, i.e., the rump or tail-bone, which passes over into the vertebrae of the tail (cf. Bochart, i. pp. 560-1). In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 3:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the fat portions which were burned are called \"food of the firing for Jehovah,\" or \"food of the firing for a sweet savour,\" i.e., food which served as a firing for Jehovah, or reached Jehovah by being burned; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
